-- Swiss Stocks Gain for Fourth Day as U.S. Jobless Claims Decline
-- B y   P e t e r   L e v r i n g
-- 2011-12-22T16:48:27Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-22/swiss-stocks-rise-before-u-s-data-adecco-transocean-advance.html
Swiss stocks  rose for a fourth day
as the number of applications for U.S. unemployment benefits
dropped to the lowest since April 2008, a sign that the world’s
largest economy is strengthening.  Adecco SA (ADEN) , the world’s biggest supplier of temporary
workers, increased 1.8 percent. Holcim Ltd., the  second-largest
cement maker (HOLN) , advanced.  Transocean Ltd. (RIG) , which owns the biggest
fleet of offshore drilling rigs, gained 1.3 percent as oil
advanced for a fourth day in  New York .  The Swiss Market Index, a measure of the largest and most
actively traded companies, added 0.6 percent to 5,837.06 at the
close in Zurich. The gauge has climbed 3.3 percent this  month (SMI)  as
European leaders agreed on measures to cut the region’s budget
deficits and the  European Central Bank  offered unlimited loans
to shore up bank funding. The wider Swiss Performance Index rose
0.7 percent today.  “European stocks are very cheap and in the absence of bad
news, they should rise,” said Thomas Haerter, chief strategist
at Swisscanto Asset Management AG in Zurich, who helps oversee
about $67 billion. “Volumes are very low so one should be
careful about making too much of today’s market.”  The SMI is trading at 12.6 times the estimated earnings of
its companies, compared with an average valuation of 13.8 over
the past five years, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  Falling Volumes  The volume of shares changing hands across  Europe  has
fallen this week as the Christmas holiday break approaches.
Trading on the Stoxx 600 this week was 83 percent of the average
for 2011, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  U.S. claims for jobless benefits fell by 4,000 to 364,000
in the week ended Dec. 17, Labor Department figures showed today
in Washington. The median forecast of 45 economists surveyed by
Bloomberg News projected an increase to 380,000.  A separate release showed  confidence  among U.S. consumers
rose more than forecast in December, to a six-month high. The
Thomson Reuters/University of Michigan final index of consumer
sentiment climbed to 69.9 from 64.1 at the end of November. The
median estimate in a Bloomberg News survey called for 68 after a
preliminary reading of 67.7.  Adecco rose 1.8 percent to 39.17 Swiss francs and Holcim
advanced 0.6 percent to 50.10 francs as companies whose earnings
are reliant on economic growth gained.  Transocean climbed 1.3 percent to 37.65 francs as oil
gained for a fourth day in New York after U.S. crude inventories
declined the most in a decade.  UBS AG (UBSN)  and  Credit Suisse Group AG (CSGN) , the biggest Swiss
lenders, advanced 3.1 percent to 11.23 francs and 1.1 percent to
21.88 francs, respectively. Banking shares were the best
performers in the  Stoxx 600 .  To contact the reporter on this story:
